<font color="#FF0000">EXPLANATION</font><br>
<tt>Mon Nov  3 17:42:51 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I know this is a bit after the fact but I think this needs to be said her because of what I wrote above on this thread asking for help.  I want to give special thanks to Tom and SW for sharing their insights.<br><br>
One of the ways I got by in Vietnam was by denying that anyone I knew had died as a result of service in Vietnam.  If people disappeared overnight from the ward, we asked nothing.  Many were sent on with serious injuries.  We never tried to find out what became of them.  We were afraid to ask. By not asking they were at least still alive in my mind. Actually I know that it has to be impossible to have served a tour in Nam and for that to be true.  Years later it has bothered me that I have no names of anyone on the wall.  Grieving for those who died is an important part of healing.  A good friend shared the story of one of his brothers who was blown away by a landmine and up to now, I have held ōJarheadö as a representative of all the men who I may have known whose names are on the wall.  <br><br>
The post about the Jolly 365 hit me like a brick wall putting a chunk in what has been a twenty five year defense mechanism by bringing the story back to mind and listing names of men who died or were taken as prisoners during a time which was very stressful for all of us who were in- country and I Corp at the time.  The 196th provided tower guards to the 95th, I partied with the bomber pilots and on a number of occassions sat in their club area waiting for them to come back off runs  - sweating out whether those who were late would be back, as well as the navy guys from Red Rocks that taught a number of us ladies to fire a weapon and lay a charge. <br><br>
Many of the posts which followed what I wrote indicated there was a misunderstanding on what I was saying. What was clear to me was clear to me.  Obviously not so clear to everyone else.  I know we went back for downed and separated men whenever possible. I didnÆt mean to imply it was wrong to do so.  <br><br>
I had a distinction in my mind about this particular situation.  What I was upset about was that in my mind there was one reason why Hambleton was in Vietnam.  That was to get combat time in for a promotion and in the process he got a whole bunch of good men killed.  That infuriated me.<br>
Maybe I was wrong.... but that was my opinion.  SW you indicated that you had men on board that would hand you a list of areas they could not fly over and for yourself death was an easier option.  I couldn't help but ask why was he there, was there a military purpose or function that only he could meet. Was there a greater meaning in the death of these men.   I was not trying to say that rescue attempts are wrong. Or that someone shouldn't go in and attempt to haul his rear out of there.  I know that is exactly the kind of thing that happened all the time.  I also know there were times that friendly fire was called in on our guys in the field.  Also, that all rescue attempts werenÆt successful.  <br><br>
I was unaware of the Bat 21 movie. And, despite EdwardÆs thought that what I was saying was based upon book learning, I was speaking from experience not anything I had read anywhere except for the guys name.  The movie indicated that Hambleton thought of the idea for an advance run and then volunteered for the surveillance aircraft trip. In the script for which Hambleton  was a consultant , one of the other men on the flight said &quot;you must have your eyes set on full bird.&quot;  Of course he denied it.   So my thought prior to seeing the movie, that Hambleton was trying to advance his career, wasn't a novel one.   But once explained, the purpose of the mission to flushing out  missiles and launch sites seems reasonable.  One could make the argument that from that perspective their mission was sucessful, that our side learned of the hand-held heat seeking missiles from his downing.  For a cherry to combat, Hambleton seemed to handle himself well, and did alot of damage to the enemy. One has to make the best out of a bad situation.  I am consoling myself with the thought that the loss of  lives in this mission saved many others in the ensuing offensive.  You tell me if that is a reasonable assumption.  <br><br>
I miss those who didnÆt come home from Vietnam.  Tom, Udo C.J. Fischers poem ōNo Moreö means a lot to me and touches an emotional chord within me.  When I am at the Wall this year, I will be thinking especially of your friend Al and the others who gave their lives to save others.<br><br>

